Honestly, I'm not sure why this spot has such low reviews. I don't know what the ambiance was like prior to COVID but I must say that I was thoroughly impressed with everything about my experience here. First off, it's a little gem in the middle of the block. I went on a Wednesday afternoon and the place was mostly empty. They have a cute little Patio area so you're not dining in the street like at some of these other restaurants during this pandemic. As soon as we were seated a waitress came over and assisted us. We ordered tacos and quesadillas and they were delicious and extremely affordable. The drinks were also strong and delicious. They also have hookah available for $25 which is a huge plus because places are charging $35-$45 for hookah these days (Just make sure you have cash to pay for the hookah and the refills are $15). After a while it started raining and what seemed like the manager and some other guys put these huge lit tents over everyone and we were safe and sound enjoying the evening despite the rain. All in all, I'll give this place a 10 out of 10. The staff was extremely sweet and prompt! This is definitely my new go to for the summer !  Disclaimer: I am EXTREMELY picky when it comes to customer service and my experiences at places so definitely take heed to my review :)

Myself, my husband and two year old daughter visited this establishment today. We live in the neighborhood and love supporting local businesses. We called at 12:10pm and made a reservation for 3 and the reservation process went well. Unfortunately when we arrived we were then informed that we would be dining on the sidewalk dining area and not within the patio area due to a private event. It would be a conscious move to be sure to inform the clients of their seating area prior to their arrival. We were then seated within the sidewalk dining area and were brought over a code to scan with your phone’s camera  for the menu and a physical drink menu as well. Our server was very nice. She gave us a few moments to view menu and when we were ready she took our orders. We waited quite some time to receive our drinks as well as food. Service wasn’t very attentive. While dining I noticed multiple staff members going in and out of the patio area WITHOUT masks on. I have a health condition and needed to use the restroom. I did not have a mask and asked our server if I could use the bathroom. I informed her that I had no mask and asked to purchase one. She said “ no worries” and began to escort me to the indoor restroom. Upon entering the patio I passed two staff members who were engaged in conversation with no masks on at the hostess stand. As I continued to follow the server to the restroom I hear a woman yelling “ miss where are you going where are you going what are you doing here?!” This came from the non mask wearing hostess who let me pass her while she was engaged in conversation with her co worker. I told her I was a guest eating outside and needed to use the bathroom. “ you need a mask you need a mask! You can’t come in here without a mask!” The hostess continued to yell while having her sunglasses on and no mask. I explained to her that I was aware of the rules and had requested a mask and was told it was ok. Whoever this blonde woman at the hostess stand for the patio was, she was incredibly rude and unprofessional. You want a guest to wear a mask but you have no mask on yourself ? ! I turned around went back outside furious. Our server came back to me apologizing and gave me a mask. I went into the actual indoor establishment and NO ONE IN THERE STAFF OR ANYONE HAD THEIR MASKS ON! Clearly if guests need to come in to use the restroom you should have to wear you mask as well! Protection works both ways for the employees and clients. I went to wait for the bathroom on a line that was basically all bottle service girls waiting to change and do their make up for today’s event. I don’t think a client should have to wait behind staff when they are paying for a service. I didn’t use the restroom here.  The food here is really good but the service and professionalism is out the window.  We spent over $100 here just for lunch. We left a great tip for our server as well.  My tips to the establishment: Teach your staff to be professional, learn how to speak respectfully to everyone they come in contact with, learn to be empathetic and most of all lead by example and WEAR YOUR MASKS!

As far as high priced Dominican restaurants in East New York go, this has to be near the top of the list. What's unfortunate for this clean and usually empty locale is the plethora of (much cheaper) Dominican restaurants in the area. Yes, the food is decent here but the Manhattan prices just don't fly on Brooklyn's Fulton Street. The restaurant's happy hour is unparalleled (2 ice cold beers for $5!) and their outdoor space is huge, inviting and the J train's rumble, every so often, gives it character. I'd say come for the happy hour, that runs from 4-9pm, and then head up to the lounge upstairs once it opens up. There's brunch every Saturday and Sunday that I've yet to experience but I hear is pretty popular.
